<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: EDUCATION: INGLEWOOD TO HOLD SCHOOL LOTTERY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JON GARCIA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A lottery will be held for students who want to switch schools in Inglewood. 
</P>
<P>
 The school board, which used to allow transfers on a first-come, first-served 
basis, has changed its policy to fit state guidelines on open enrollment. 
</P>
<P>
 Students who want to transfer must apply for a permit. All transfers will 
based on available space at the school, and beginning in the fall, the names of 
students for open slots will be picked at random, said Joice Bailey Lewis, 
director of pupil services.  
</P>
<P>
 Students who attend their local school will not be displaced by transfer 
applicants. 
</P>
<P>
 Under the new guidelines, applicants who cite hardship as a reason for 
transfer will no longer be given preferential treatment.  
</P>
<P>
 The policy does not apply to those who want to transfer outside of the 
district. JON GARCIA 
</P>
</TEXT>
