<HEADLINE>
<P>
HISTORY: PRESERVING MIRACLE MILE BUILDINGS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 I've lived in the Miracle Mile district all my life; my Mom grew up there, too 
("What Price History," May 22). Granted, we do not have buildings such as the 
Taj Mahal or a showcase designed by Frank Lloyd Wright, but the 1920s buildings 
and apartments are all we have to crow about.It's our architectural heritage! 
</P>
<P>
 Somehow it doesn't surprise me that landlords in the Miracle Mile South 
district desire to tear down these buildings. It appears to be a ritual here in 
Los Angeles to demolish older, quaint buildings to accommodate a parking lot or 
another apartment building. 
</P>
<P>
 I agree with Denise Robb of the Miracle Mile Action Committee -- if I see one 
more balloon-laden apartment building in the Miracle Mile area, I'll scream. 
And as for landlord Host Beil, who said, "There's no reason for a building from 
1929 to be a historical monument" and "I was born in Germany, and my town goes 
back thousands of years," all I can say is: Sorry, Mr. Beil, we're a few 
thousand years behind. Give us a chance to catch up. Start by preserving the 
buildings in the Miracle Mile South area. 
</P>
<P>
 LINDA HARRIS 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles  
</P>
</TEXT>
