<HEADLINE>
<P>
PERSONAL VIEW: EXECUTIVE TRAVEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * Name: William Abowd, AlarmNet, Marina del Rey 
</P>
<P>
 * Position: Regional sales director 
</P>
<P>
 Almost all frequent fliers know the value of accumulating frequent-flier 
mileage points. We know you can earn miles by flying on a particular airline, 
but there are many other ways to watch your mileage statements grow. 
</P>
<P>
 One is by using credit cards. I charge everything I can on my 
airline-affiliated credit cards. That includes business expenses. I always use 
personal credit cards rather than company-issued cards on business outings, 
simply to obtain the miles. 
</P>
<P>
 Many distributors accept credit cards, and I have seen people earn several 
hundred thousand miles a year by charging company expenses on the card. 
However, some card providers and airlines now limit the number of miles that 
can be earned with them.  
</P>
<P>
 You can also earn miles with the phone. I spend about $1,000 a month on 
long-distance calls that earn five miles for every dollar spent. That comes to 
5,000 frequent-flier miles a month. If you travel frequently on a particular 
airline, you can quickly reach "premium" status and accumulate credits more 
quickly. For example, I flew 60,000 miles in one year on Delta and reached the 
Royal Medallion level. Now my miles are credited at 1 1/2 times the rate of 
other fliers. The miles really add up fast. 
</P>
<P>
 By using the same airline (and rental car companies and hotels), I accumulate 
frequent-user program benefits fast. You too will be traveling for free!  
</P>
<P>
 I apologize to my travel agent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
